---
import CalcolatoreLayout from '../../layouts/CalcolatoreLayout.astro';
import PagaOraria from '../../components/calcolatori/PagaOraria';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
import { canonicalURL } from '../../lib/seo';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = "Hourly Rate Calculator Italy 2026: Gross and Net Pay";
const description = "Convert your gross annual salary (RAL) into gross and net hourly rate. Factors in weekly hours, CCNL contract type, and 2026 Italian tax rules automatically.";
const canonical = canonicalURL('/en/hourly-rate-calculator/');

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'Hourly Rate Calculator', url: canonical },
];
---

<CalcolatoreLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  calculatorName="Hourly Rate Calculator"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  canonical={canonical}
  lang={lang}
>
  <PagaOraria client:load lang={lang} />

  <Fragment slot="come-si-calcola">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      How to Calculate Your Hourly Rate from RAL in Italy
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        To calculate your gross hourly rate (paga oraria lorda), you divide your
        RAL (Retribuzione Annua Lorda, or gross annual salary) by the total
        number of hours actually worked in a year. In Italy, a standard
        full-time contract (contratto a tempo pieno) typically requires 40 hours
        per week across roughly 52 weeks. However, you must subtract the hours
        accounted for by paid holidays (ferie), public holidays (festivita'),
        and contractual leave days (permessi or ROL). The resulting figure
        typically falls between 1,720 and 1,760 effective working hours per
        year, depending on which CCNL (Contratto Collettivo Nazionale di
        Lavoro -- national collective bargaining agreement) applies to your
        employment relationship.
      </p>

      <h3>From Gross Hourly Pay to Net Hourly Pay</h3>
      <p>
        Your net hourly rate (paga oraria netta) is obtained by dividing your
        annual net salary by the same number of effective working hours.
        Alternatively, you can apply the average deduction percentages directly
        to your gross hourly figure. These deductions include INPS employee
        contributions (9.19% of gross pay), IRPEF income tax (progressive rates
        from 23% to 43%), and the regional and municipal surcharges (addizionali
        regionali e comunali), which vary depending on where you are registered
        as a resident. The net hourly rate tells you how much you truly earn
        for every hour of work after all taxes and contributions -- a crucial
        data point when comparing job offers, evaluating whether overtime is
        worth it, or deciding between employment and freelancing.
      </p>

      <h3>Why Knowing Your Hourly Rate Matters</h3>
      <p>
        Understanding your real hourly pay is essential for a wide range of
        financial decisions, especially if you are an expat weighing different
        career paths in Italy. It helps you evaluate whether a salary increase
        genuinely compensates for longer working hours, compare an employee
        offer against a freelance contract (partita IVA), decide if overtime
        (straordinario) is financially worthwhile at your marginal tax rate, and
        assess whether switching to part-time work makes economic sense. For
        professionals who relocated to Italy and may be comparing compensation
        to their home country, the hourly rate provides a clean, apples-to-apples
        benchmark that strips away differences in annual leave policies and
        pay structure.
      </p>

      <h3>Effective Working Hours in Italy by CCNL Contract Type</h3>
      <p>
        Not all national collective agreements (CCNL) prescribe the same annual
        hours. The number of hours you actually work depends on three main
        variables: paid annual leave (ferie), public holidays (festivita'), and
        contractual paid leave hours known as ROL (Riduzione Orario di Lavoro).
        Here is how these components differ across the most common Italian
        employment contracts and the impact they have on your hourly rate
        calculation.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>CCNL Metalmeccanico</strong> (metalworking and engineering
        sector) is the most widely applied collective agreement in Italy,
        covering over 1.5 million workers. It sets a standard schedule of
        40 hours per week. After subtracting 4 weeks of mandatory annual leave
        (160 hours), public holidays falling on working days (roughly 10 days,
        equalling 80 hours), and ROL leave (104 hours for companies with more
        than 15 employees; 72 hours for smaller firms), you arrive at
        approximately <strong>1,720 effective working hours</strong> per year.
        This is the reference value most commonly used in hourly rate
        calculations across Italy.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>CCNL Commercio e Terziario</strong> (retail, trade, and
        services sector), governed by Confcommercio, covers over 2 million
        workers in retail distribution, services, and tourism. The contractual
        schedule is also 40 hours per week, but ROL entitlements are lower:
        56 hours per year for companies with up to 15 employees and 72 hours
        for larger firms. Adding up annual leave (160 hours) and public holidays
        (approximately 80 hours), the result is around <strong>1,752 effective
        hours</strong> -- slightly more than the metalworking contract.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>CCNL Bancari e Credito</strong> (banking and financial
        services sector) is notable for its more generous terms. The standard
        working week is 37.5 hours (7 hours and 30 minutes per day), annual
        leave can reach 25-27 working days depending on seniority, and
        additional leave days are granted for abolished public holidays (ex
        festivita' soppresse). Effective annual hours drop to roughly
        <strong>1,650 hours</strong>, which means that at the same RAL, a
        banking employee's gross hourly rate is noticeably higher than in other
        sectors.
      </p>
      <p>
        Regarding <strong>annual leave (ferie)</strong>, Italian law (Legislative
        Decree 66/2003) mandates a minimum of 4 weeks per year (20 working
        days). Many CCNLs, however, grant additional days linked to seniority:
        for instance, the CCNL Metalmeccanico provides 22 days after 10 years
        of service and 25 days after 18 years. If you are new to Italy, you
        should be aware that your employer cannot reduce your leave below the
        statutory 4-week minimum under any circumstances.
      </p>
      <p>
        Italy has <strong>11 national public holidays</strong> (from January 1st
        through December 25th, including Republic Day on June 2nd and Labour
        Day on May 1st). In addition, each municipality designates a patron
        saint's day (Santo Patrono) as a local holiday. On average, about
        10-12 of these holidays fall on working days in any given year, though
        the exact number varies with the calendar. When a public holiday falls
        on a weekend, Italian employees generally do not receive a compensatory
        day off, unlike in some other European countries.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>ROL (Riduzione Orario di Lavoro)</strong>, or contractual
        reduced working-time hours, are paid leave hours that vary significantly
        across different CCNLs: from as few as 32 hours per year under the CCNL
        Studi Professionali (professional offices) to 104 hours under the CCNL
        Metalmeccanico for companies with more than 15 employees. ROL not used
        within the contractual deadline are paid out in the payslip (monetizzati
        in busta paga), but actually taking them means fewer hours worked and
        therefore a higher real hourly rate.
      </p>

      <h3>Employee vs. Freelance: The True Cost Comparison</h3>
      <p>
        One of the most common mistakes -- particularly among expats evaluating
        whether to work as an employee (lavoratore dipendente) or open a
        partita IVA (VAT number for self-employment) -- is to compare the net
        hourly rate of an employee directly with the hourly fee of a freelancer.
        In reality, the total cost of employing someone in Italy is
        significantly higher than the RAL shown on the employment contract, and
        this hidden cost represents tangible benefits that a freelancer must
        fund independently.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here are the key employer-borne costs that enrich the employee's total
        compensation package beyond the visible RAL:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>TFR (Trattamento di Fine Rapporto -- severance pay)</strong>
        amounts to approximately 6.91% of the RAL. It is a form of deferred
        compensation that the employee receives upon termination of the
        employment relationship, or that flows into a supplementary pension
        fund (fondo pensione complementare). For a RAL of 30,000 euros, the TFR
        is worth roughly 2,073 euros per year -- money that a freelancer does
        not receive and would need to set aside independently for retirement
        savings.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Employer social security contributions (contributi
        previdenziali a carico del datore di lavoro)</strong> amount to 23.81%
        of the RAL for the INPS pension component (IVS), plus additional
        contributions for sickness, maternity, unemployment insurance (NASpI),
        family allowances, and INAIL workplace accident insurance. The total can
        reach 30-32% of the RAL. For an employee with a RAL of 30,000 euros,
        the employer pays approximately 9,000-9,600 euros in contributions -- a
        massive amount that a freelancer under the flat-rate regime (regime
        forfettario) covers independently at 26.23% of taxable income through
        the INPS gestione separata.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Paid holidays and leave</strong> represent a substantial
        indirect cost. A full-time employee enjoys approximately 30-35 days of
        paid absence per year between annual leave, public holidays, and ROL.
        A freelancer, by contrast, earns nothing on days when no work is
        performed: no paid holidays, no paid sick leave, no paid leave of any
        kind. Considering that a freelancer typically has 220-230 billable days
        per year versus an employee's roughly 252 working days (of which around
        30 are paid without working), the gap is substantial.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Paid sick leave and maternity leave</strong> are further
        advantages of employment. During illness, an employee receives between
        50% and 100% of regular pay (depending on the CCNL and the duration
        of absence), with costs split between INPS and the employer. Mandatory
        maternity leave (congedo di maternita' obbligatorio) provides 80% of
        salary from INPS, often topped up to 100% by the employer. Freelancers
        under the gestione separata receive only a basic INPS allowance,
        calculated on generally lower amounts.
      </p>
      <p>
        On top of all this, many employers offer <strong>fringe benefits
        (benefit aziendali)</strong> that are common in Italian salaried
        employment: meal vouchers (buoni pasto, up to 8 euros per day tax-free
        if electronic), supplementary health insurance (assicurazione sanitaria
        integrativa), professional training, company cars, and corporate welfare
        plans. These benefits can add 5% to 15% of the RAL in value.
      </p>
      <p>
        For all these reasons, the rule of thumb is that a <strong>freelance
        hourly rate should be at least 2 to 2.5 times the net hourly rate of
        an employee</strong> to guarantee an equivalent standard of living. For
        example, if an employee earns 12 euros net per hour, a freelancer would
        need to invoice at least 24-30 euros per hour to achieve a comparable
        level of protection and savings.
      </p>

      <h3>Hourly Pay Benchmarks by Industry in Italy</h3>
      <p>
        Hourly pay varies enormously by industry, reflecting differences in
        value added, scarcity of specialized skills, and collective bargaining
        power. Here is an overview of the main sectors with their typical gross
        hourly pay ranges for full-time, permanent positions (tempo pieno e
        indeterminato).
      </p>
      <p>
        In the <strong>IT and technology</strong> sector, gross hourly pay
        typically ranges from 18 to 35 euros. Entry-level roles (junior
        developer, help desk, tester) start at 18-22 euros, while senior and
        specialist profiles (cloud architect, data engineer, cybersecurity
        specialist, senior DevOps) comfortably reach 30-35 euros. Managerial
        positions (CTO, VP Engineering) exceed 40 euros gross per hour.
        Persistent demand exceeding supply sustains year-on-year pay growth,
        especially for skills in artificial intelligence, cybersecurity, and
        cloud computing.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>finance and banking</strong> sector offers gross hourly pay
        between 20 and 40 euros. Branch-level operational roles (tellers,
        customer service) fall in the 20-25 euro range, while financial
        analysts, risk managers, and compliance officers reach 28-35 euros.
        Front-office positions in investment banking and private banking can
        significantly exceed 40 euros gross per hour, excluding variable bonuses
        which in this sector can represent a substantial share of total
        compensation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Manufacturing and industry</strong> shows a range of 12 to 20
        euros gross per hour. Skilled workers and production technicians
        generally fall between 12 and 16 euros, while qualified technical roles
        (mechanical designers, quality managers, process engineers) reach 18-20
        euros. The CCNL Metalmeccanico, with its grading structure from C1 to
        D2 for quadri (middle managers), defines minimum contractual pay levels
        (minimi tabellari) that are often supplemented by individual top-ups
        (superminimi individuali) and production bonuses.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>retail and large-scale distribution (GDO)</strong> sector
        has among the lowest hourly rates, in the range of 10-15 euros gross.
        Sales assistants and retail workers earn 10-12 euros, while department
        heads and store managers reach 13-15 euros. The prevalence of
        involuntary part-time in this sector further reduces total annual
        income, even though the nominal gross hourly rate remains unchanged
        compared to full-time. Large retail chains (GDO) tend to offer slightly
        better conditions than independent shops.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the <strong>healthcare sector (Sanita')</strong>, gross hourly pay
        ranges from 15 to 25 euros. Professional nurses (infermieri
        professionisti) fall in the 15-19 euro bracket, while hospital-employed
        doctors earn between 20 and 25 euros. It is worth noting that public
        sector salaries tend to be lower than the private sector but are offset
        by greater job security, better pension benefits, and in many cases
        fewer annual working hours. A chronic shortage of healthcare
        professionals, worsened since the pandemic, is starting to push
        compensation upward, particularly for the most in-demand specialties
        such as anaesthesia, emergency medicine, and intensive care.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="valori">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      Hourly Rate by RAL Level: Comparative Reference Table
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The following table converts various RAL (gross annual salary) levels
        into gross hourly rates, estimated net hourly rates, and the equivalent
        freelance rate needed to achieve a comparable standard of living. All
        calculations are based on 1,720 effective working hours per year (CCNL
        Metalmeccanico standard), using 2026 IRPEF tax brackets, employee INPS
        contributions at 9.19%, and average regional and municipal surcharges.
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="min-w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600">
              <th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">RAL (Gross Annual)</th>
              <th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Gross Hourly (1,720h)</th>
              <th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Est. Net Hourly</th>
              <th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Freelance Equivalent</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200 dark:divide-gray-700">
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">20,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">11.63 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~8.40 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~17-21 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">25,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">14.53 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~10.50 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~21-26 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">30,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">17.44 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~12.30 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~25-31 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">40,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">23.26 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~15.70 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~31-39 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">50,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">29.07 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~18.70 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~37-47 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">60,000 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">34.88 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~21.70 &euro;</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">~43-54 &euro;</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Looking at the table, a clear <strong>non-linear relationship between
        RAL and net hourly pay</strong> emerges. When RAL doubles from 20,000 to
        40,000 euros, the gross hourly rate doubles proportionally (from 11.63
        to 23.26 euros), but the net hourly rate increases by only about 87%
        (from 8.40 to 15.70 euros). This compression effect is caused by the
        progressive nature of IRPEF: as income rises, an increasing share is
        taxed at higher marginal rates (from 23% on the first 28,000 euros to
        43% on income above 50,000 euros). Employment income tax deductions
        (detrazioni da lavoro dipendente) also gradually phase out and reach
        zero for incomes above 50,000 euros, further amplifying the compression
        of net pay relative to gross. This dynamic makes it particularly
        important to focus on your net hourly rate rather than reasoning solely
        in gross terms: two job offers with very different RAL figures may have
        net hourly rates that are closer than you would expect.
      </p>
      <p>
        For expats comparing Italian salaries to those in other countries, keep
        in mind that the Italian tax wedge (cuneo fiscale) -- the gap between
        what the employer pays and what the employee takes home -- is among the
        highest in the OECD. At a RAL of 35,000 euros, the total employer cost
        is roughly 47,000 euros, but the employee takes home approximately
        24,000 euros net. Understanding this context is critical when
        negotiating compensation packages or evaluating relocation offers.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="faq">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      Frequently Asked Questions
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How many working hours are there in a year in Italy?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          With a standard full-time contract of 40 hours per week, the total annual hours come to approximately 2,080 (40 x 52). After subtracting annual leave (ferie, typically 4 weeks), public holidays (festivita', around 10 working days), and contractual leave (ROL, which varies by CCNL), you arrive at approximately 1,720-1,760 effective working hours. The exact number depends on your CCNL and the specific year's calendar. For instance, the CCNL Metalmeccanico yields about 1,720 hours, while the CCNL Commercio yields roughly 1,752 hours.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How do I compare employee hourly pay to a freelance rate in Italy?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          A direct comparison is misleading. As an employee (lavoratore dipendente), your hourly pay includes substantial hidden benefits: TFR severance accrual (approximately +7% of RAL), employer pension contributions (+24% or more), paid annual leave, paid sick days, and often meal vouchers or supplementary health insurance. As a freelancer (libero professionista with partita IVA), you must cover all these costs independently, plus professional expenses and periods without client work. The general rule is that a freelance hourly rate needs to be at least double the employee's net hourly rate to be truly equivalent in terms of total compensation and financial security.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Does the calculation include overtime hours?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          No, the calculation is based on standard contractual hours only. Overtime hours (straordinario) in Italy are paid with a premium that ranges from 15% to 30% or more, depending on the CCNL, the day (weekday, weekend, or public holiday), and whether the work is performed at night. If you regularly work overtime, your effective hourly rate will differ from the figure calculated here, because the overtime premium increases your annual net pay but must be divided across a larger number of total hours. For example, under the CCNL Metalmeccanico, the first 2 daily overtime hours on a weekday carry a 25% premium, subsequent hours carry 30%, Sunday overtime 50%, and night-time holiday overtime 55%.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How does the hourly rate change with a part-time contract?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The gross hourly rate for a part-time contract is identical to that of a full-time worker with the same contractual classification (inquadramento). Only the total number of hours worked changes. However, the net hourly rate may differ slightly because lower annual income places the worker in lower IRPEF tax brackets, resulting in lower marginal tax rates and a proportionally greater impact from employment tax deductions (detrazioni da lavoro dipendente). In practice, this means a part-time worker often has a slightly higher net hourly rate than a full-time colleague at the same classification level.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          What is the average hourly rate in Italy?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          According to ISTAT (the Italian National Statistics Institute) data, the average gross hourly wage in Italy is approximately 16-17 euros. However, the range is very wide: from 9-10 euros per hour for the lowest-qualified roles (manual labourers, cleaning staff) to over 40-50 euros per hour for executives and specialized professionals. Region and sector also significantly influence this figure -- Northern Italy generally pays 10-20% more than the South for equivalent roles. Compared to other EU countries, Italy's average hourly pay is above Spain and Portugal but below Germany, France, and the Nordic countries.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          What is the difference between horizontal and vertical part-time?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          In a horizontal part-time arrangement (part-time orizzontale), the employee works every day of the week but with reduced daily hours (e.g., 4 hours per day instead of 8). In a vertical part-time arrangement (part-time verticale), the employee works full-time hours but only on certain days of the week (e.g., 3 out of 5 days) or during specific periods of the year. The gross hourly rate is identical in both cases and matches that of a full-time worker at the same classification level. The main difference concerns the net hourly rate: in vertical part-time, concentrating hours into fewer days can result in higher annual income compared to horizontal part-time with the same percentage, potentially pushing the worker into a higher IRPEF bracket and thus affecting the net pay per hour worked. Additionally, in vertical part-time, annual leave (ferie) and ROL accrue proportionally to the days actually worked, which affects the calculation of effective annual hours.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How much is an overtime hour worth in Italy?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The value of an overtime hour depends on the applicable CCNL and the type of overtime. Italian law (Legislative Decree 66/2003) mandates a minimum premium of 10%, but most CCNLs set higher rates. Under the CCNL Metalmeccanico, for example, the premium is 25% for the first 2 weekday overtime hours, 30% for subsequent hours, 50% for Sunday/public holiday overtime, and 55% for night-time holiday overtime. To calculate the actual value, multiply your standard gross hourly rate by the premium factor: with a base rate of 17 euros/hour, one weekday overtime hour is worth approximately 21.25 euros gross. Important: overtime is subject to standard income taxation, so the net increase is less than the gross premium -- especially for workers already in higher IRPEF brackets (35% above 28,000 euros or 43% above 50,000 euros).
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          How do I compare hourly pay across different countries?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Comparing hourly pay across countries requires several adjustments for a meaningful comparison. First, you must account for the different number of hours worked annually: approximately 1,350 in Germany, 1,520 in France, 1,720 in Italy, and 1,670 in the United Kingdom. Then you need to factor in the cost of living through purchasing power parity (PPP): 20 euros per hour in Milan does not buy the same goods and services as 20 euros per hour in Berlin or 20 pounds in London. Furthermore, tax and social security systems differ radically: some countries (like Denmark) have low social contributions but very high income taxes, while others (like France) have high social contributions but more extensive public services. For a realistic comparison, the best approach is to calculate the net hourly rate adjusted for local cost of living, using indices such as the Big Mac Index, Eurostat cost-of-living indicators, or the Numbeo Cost of Living Index. For expats considering a move to Italy, also remember to account for benefits like the Impatriati tax regime, which can reduce your taxable income by 50-70% for the first 5-10 years.
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between px-6 py-4 text-gray-900 dark:text-white font-medium">
          Does the Impatriati tax regime affect my hourly rate calculation?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0l-4.25-4.25a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-6 pb-4 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes, significantly. The Regime Impatriati (also known as the "rientro dei cervelli" or brain-return incentive) allows qualifying workers who transfer their tax residence to Italy to benefit from a substantial reduction in taxable employment income -- historically 70% exempt (taxing only 30%), though recent reforms have modified the percentages for new applicants. This dramatically increases your net hourly rate for the duration of the benefit (typically 5 years, extendable to 10 under certain conditions). For example, an employee with a RAL of 50,000 euros who qualifies for the regime might see their net hourly rate jump from approximately 18.70 euros to around 24-25 euros. If you are an expat who recently moved to Italy or is considering doing so, use our <a href="/en/impatriati-tax-regime/" class="underline hover:text-brand">Impatriati Tax Regime calculator</a> for precise figures.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
